{"task": "section_extraction", "schema_version": "v1", "prompt_version": "trek_metadata_v1", "trek_id": "ali-bedni-bugyal-trek", "trek_title": "Ali Bedni Bugyal Trek", "section_id": "ali-bedni-bugyal-trek::itinerary_day-002", "section_type": "itinerary_day", "source_field": "day_wise_itinerary[1]", "source_url": "https://indiahikes.com/ali-bedni-bugyal-trek", "section_text": "{
  "day": "2",
  "place_title": "Day 2: Drive from Lohajung to Wan. Trek to Gehroli Patal",
  "difficulty": "Difficulty: Easy-Moderate. This day is full of ascent from Wan to Gehroli Patal",
  "duration": "Trek Duration: 6 hours | Trek Distance: 6.3 km",
  "altitude": "Altitude gain: 7,550 ft to 10,350 ft",
  "water_sources": "Water sources: Carry sufficient water. You will cross streams intermittently where you can refill your water bottles.",
  "description": "You’ll start by taking a vehicle from Lohajung to Wan. It’s a drive of about 45 mins.\nThe initial trail from Wan is cemented through a cluster of houses. 15 minutes into your trek, you will find a cluster of centuries-old Cypress trees. It would take four people to circumvent the tree! Try hugging it.\nFrom here, there are two trails you can spot. One goes straight ahead to the ridge. The second one acts as a deviation from the Latu Devta temple. Latu Devta is a local deity, who is believed to protect the area.  The mountain folk pay obeisance to him before ascending higher on the Nanda Devi Jat Yatra. Ring the temple bell here for a safe trek before going back to the ascending trail to the ridge – Ranaka Dhar. It takes 30-45 minutes to ascend from Wan to Ranaka Dhar. At Ranaka Dhar, take in the view of Lohajung, Wan and the valley below!\nFrom here, it is a short descent to the iconinc Neel Ganga. The bridge on Neel Ganga is an idyllic location to take a breather. Trees overhang the river and the water trips and fall over boulders in the shade. The water here is cool and refreshing.\nFrom here begins the beautiful continuous ascent to the first campsite, Gehroli Patal. The trail now winds through Oak and Rhododendron forests and the path is strewn with dry leaves that crunch and crackle beneath your trekking shoes. There are walnut, pear, Himalayan roses and other flora you can find on this climb. You may even spot birds like a flycatcher, and magpies. Keep a lookout.\nThis is a trek of about 3 hours that brings you to a clearing with a green trekker’s hut and the welcome sight of Trishul. This is Gehroli Patal.\nOn a clear day, you get astounding views of Mt Trishul commandeering over the area. Set up camp here."
}", "categories_to_extract": ["identity", "geography_and_logistics", "difficulty", "fitness", "age_and_group_suitability", "seasonality", "experience_themes", "risks_and_watchouts", "itinerary_profile", "recommendation_profile", "comparison_axes"]}

{"task": "section_extraction", "schema_version": "v1", "prompt_version": "trek_metadata_v1", "trek_id": "ali-bedni-bugyal-trek", "trek_title": "Ali Bedni Bugyal Trek", "section_id": "ali-bedni-bugyal-trek::itinerary_day-003", "section_type": "itinerary_day", "source_field": "day_wise_itinerary[2]", "source_url": "https://indiahikes.com/ali-bedni-bugyal-trek", "section_text": "{
  "day": "3",
  "place_title": "Day 3: Trek from Gehroli Patal to Abin Kharak via Bedni Top",
  "difficulty": "Difficulty: Easy-Moderate. Short climb with rolling meadows followed by a slightly steep ascent to Bedni Top and a gradual descent to Abin Kharak.",
  "duration": "Trek Duration: 4 hours | Trek Distance: 5.70 km",
  "altitude": "Altitude gain: 10,350 ft to 11,145 ft via 12,550 ft",
  "water_sources": "Water sources: Carry sufficient water. No water sources on the way.",
  "description": "Start your day with a climb through the oak and Rhododendron forest. The trail takes a steep ascent and crosses the tree line, leading you straight to Bedni Bugyal. Far ahead, hundreds of meters is the famous Bedni Kund.\nFrom here, just 800 metres away is the highest point on the trek, the Bedni Top. You get the best views from the top. Mt Trishul and Mt Nanda Ghunti appear right in front of you.\nThe weather fluctuates in these parts and you can have moments of wild sunshine followed by anxious cloud cover. Keep your raincoat handy. Sometimes it rains for a few minutes leaving you frustrated, at times it could rain for a few hours.\nFrom Bedni Top, descend down to the main trail.  You need to stick to this main trail. This is the trail which takes one to the famous trek of Roopkund.\nThe opposite side is Ali Bugyal and takes the gradual descent. Takes a sharp turn on the ledge hugging the mountains.\nNow leisurely walk your way to Ali Bugyal, 2 km away and more or less at the same level.\nClouds drift in from below, glide over the ridge and slide down either side, all in a slow, swift motion. You watch countless horses grazing on the bounty of nature. Foals tearing themselves across the turf in an uninhibited abandon, just being themselves.\nFrom Ali Bugyal, Abin Kharak campsite is on the left side of the ridge and in a depression in the bugyal. Stay the night here."
}", "categories_to_extract": ["identity", "geography_and_logistics", "difficulty", "fitness", "age_and_group_suitability", "seasonality", "experience_themes", "risks_and_watchouts", "itinerary_profile", "recommendation_profile", "comparison_axes"]}

